DataElement.preferredDefinition: A defined organization or layout representing and structuring data in a computer file.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: A data file stored as an electronic record.:The format of an electronic file.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A data file stored as an electronic record.

Concepts.definition: A data file stored as an electronic record.

Property.preferredDefinition: The format of an electronic file.

Concepts.definition: The format of an electronic file.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: An organizational header for concepts representing mostly abstract entities.

ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: The format of an electronic file._Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited file defining how each array in an investigation is used. This data includes what sequence is located at each position in an array and what the annotation of this sequence is; cross-references to entries in a public repository can be used if available.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited file defining how each array in an investigation is used. This data includes what sequence is located at each position in an array and what the annotation of this sequence is; cross-references to entries in a public repository can be used if available.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A multimedia container format for audio video interleaved (AVI) files that allows for synchronous audio-with-video playback.

Concepts.definition: A multimedia container format for audio video interleaved (AVI) files that allows for synchronous audio-with-video playback.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An index file found in the same directory as the binary alignment map (BAM) file, a compressed binary version of a sequence alignment/map (SAM) file.

Concepts.definition: An index file found in the same directory as the binary alignment map (BAM) file, a compressed binary version of a sequence alignment/map (SAM) file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A binary representation of a sequence alignment map (SAM), a compact and indexable representation of nucleotide sequence alignments, compressed by the BGZF (Blocked GNU Zip Format) library.

Concepts.definition: A binary representation of a sequence alignment map (SAM), a compact and indexable representation of nucleotide sequence alignments, compressed by the BGZF (Blocked GNU Zip Format) library.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited text file format that allows the specification of the sequence data that is displayed in an annotation track. The minimum required information is chromosome, start position, and end position.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited text file format that allows the specification of the sequence data that is displayed in an annotation track. The minimum required information is chromosome, start position, and end position.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A format that allows display of continuous-valued data in track format. This display type is useful for probability scores and transcriptome data.

Concepts.definition: A format that allows display of continuous-valued data in track format. This display type is useful for probability scores and transcriptome data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A format for large sequence annotation tracks, similar to the textual browser extensible data (BED) format. The annotated items can be either simple or a linked collection of exons.

Concepts.definition: A format for large sequence annotation tracks, similar to the textual browser extensible data (BED) format. The annotated items can be either simple or a linked collection of exons.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A format for large sequence annotation tracks that consist of a value for each sequence position, similar to the textual wiggle (WIG) format.

Concepts.definition: A format for large sequence annotation tracks that consist of a value for each sequence position, similar to the textual wiggle (WIG) format.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format in which file information is stored in the form of ones and zeros. It can be easily converted to text representations for visualization and editing.

Concepts.definition: A file format in which file information is stored in the form of ones and zeros. It can be easily converted to text representations for visualization and editing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Files that consist of aggregate clinical and biospecimen data across all cases of the given project. Biotab files are supplemental files that are available in the Genomic Data Commons (GDC) Legacy Archive as tab-delimited files on a project level basis. These may also include fields that are not available in the GDC application programming interface (API).

Concepts.definition: Files that consist of aggregate clinical and biospecimen data across all cases of the given project. Biotab files are supplemental files that are available in the Genomic Data Commons (GDC) Legacy Archive as tab-delimited files on a project level basis. These may also include fields that are not available in the GDC application programming interface (API).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A general-use format for representing biological sample by observation contingency tables. It is designed for general use in broad areas of comparative -omics. The primary use of this format is to represent operational taxonomic unit (OTU) and metagenome tables.

Concepts.definition: A general-use format for representing biological sample by observation contingency tables. It is designed for general use in broad areas of comparative -omics. The primary use of this format is to represent operational taxonomic unit (OTU) and metagenome tables.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A more highly compressed alternative to the BAM and SAM DNA sequence alignment file formats. It uses reference based compression, with only base calls that differ from a designated reference sequence being stored.

Concepts.definition: A compressed columnar file format for storing biological sequences aligned to a reference sequence. It uses reference based compression, with only base calls that differ from a designated reference sequence being stored.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A text file format that separates data elements with commas.

Concepts.definition: A text file format that separates data elements with commas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file type that uses Open XML Document format to store data for Microsoft Word and other compatible programs.

Concepts.definition: A file type that uses Open XML Document format to store data for Microsoft Word and other compatible programs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A delimiter-separated values file that contains plain text data divided into rows and columns by a designated special character.

Concepts.definition: A delimiter-separated values file that contains plain text data divided into rows and columns by a designated special character.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sequence in FASTA format consists of a single-line description, followed by lines of sequence data. The first character of the description line is a greater-than (">") symbol in the first column.  Sequences are represented in the standard IUB/IUPAC single letter amino acid and nucleic acid codes, with a single hyphen or dash being used to represent a gap of indeterminate length; in amino acid sequences asterix ("*") can represent a translation stop.

Concepts.definition: A text-based format for representing either nucleotide sequences or peptide sequences. It consists of a single-line description, followed by lines of sequence data.  Sequences are represented in the standard IUPAC-IUB (International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry-International Union of Biochemistry Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature) single letter amino acid and nucleic acid base codes. It is an extension of the FAST-P (protein) and FAST-N (nucleotide) alignment tools.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A a tab-delimited containing information about an investigation, including its name, a description, the investigator's contact details, bibliographic references, and free text descriptions of any relevant protocols.

Concepts.definition: A a tab-delimited containing information about an investigation, including its name, a description, the investigator's contact details, bibliographic references, and free text descriptions of any relevant protocols.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited text file that contains gene expression data as a column for each sample, a row for each gene, and an expression value for each gene in each sample. RES differs from GCT by having labels for each gene's absent (A) versus present (P) calls as generated by Affymetrix's GeneChip software.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited text file that contains gene expression data as a column for each sample, a row for each gene, and an expression value for each gene in each sample. RES differs from GCT by having labels for each gene's absent (A) versus present (P) calls as generated by Affymetrix's GeneChip software.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A comprehensive set of standards for communications between medical imaging devices, including handling, storing and transmitting information in medical imaging. It includes a file format definition and a network communication protocol.

Concepts.definition: A comprehensive set of standards for communications between medical imaging devices, including handling, storing and transmitting information in medical imaging. It includes a file format definition and a network communication protocol.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of flat file format that allows for the storage of DNA or protein sequences and annotations. It consists of an annotation section and a sequence section.

Concepts.definition: A type of flat file format that allows for the storage of DNA or protein sequences and annotations. It consists of an annotation section and a sequence section.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-separated format for sequence data. It uses one line per feature, each containing 9 columns of data, plus optional track definition lines.

Concepts.definition: A tab-separated format for sequence data. It uses one line per feature, each containing 9 columns of data, plus optional track definition lines.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited text file format developed by Axon Instruments and used to export data from the microarray image analysis tool GenePix.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited text file format developed by Axon Instruments and used to export data from the microarray image analysis tool GenePix.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited text format based on the general feature format (GFF) but which also contains some additional information for each gene.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited text format based on the general feature format (GFF) but which also contains some additional information for each gene.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A hierarchical, filesystem-like data format that can store metadata in the form of user-defined, named attributes, which are attached to groups and datasets, and representations of images and tables built up using datasets, groups and attributes.

Concepts.definition: A hierarchical, filesystem-like data format that can store metadata in the form of user-defined, named attributes, which are attached to groups and datasets, and representations of images and tables built up using datasets, groups and attributes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A standard markup language used to display content on a web page, as specified by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).

Concepts.definition: A standard markup language used to display content on a web page, as specified by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format consisting of a 10-byte header containing a magic number, a version number, and a timestamp, a Deflate-compressed body, and an 8-byte footer containing a checksum and the length of the original uncompressed data.

Concepts.definition: A file format consisting of a 10-byte header containing a magic number, a version number, and a timestamp, a Deflate-compressed body, and an 8-byte footer containing a checksum and the length of the original uncompressed data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited, spreadsheet-based format that can be used for annotating and communicating microarray data in a MIAME (Minimum Information About a Microarray Experiment) compliant fashion.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited, spreadsheet-based format that can be used for annotating and communicating microarray data with experimental details in a MIAME (Minimum Information About a Microarray Experiment) compliant fashion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A proprietary, binary data container format used by MATLAB software to store workspace variables.

Concepts.definition: A proprietary, binary data container format used by MATLAB software to store workspace variables.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A multimedia file that is commonly used to store  video and audio data.

Concepts.definition: A multimedia file that is commonly used to store  video and audio data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An open-source format for mass spectrometer output files that was designed to be utilized and adapted as advances in mass spectrometry technology proceed. This was standardized by the Human Proteome Organization (HUPO)-Proteomics Standards Initiative (PSI) Mass Spectrometry Standards (MSS) Working Group.

Concepts.definition: An open-source format for mass spectrometer output files that was designed to be utilized and adapted as advances in mass spectrometry technology proceed. This was standardized by the Human Proteome Organization (HUPO)-Proteomics Standards Initiative (PSI) Mass Spectrometry Standards (MSS) Working Group.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An XML based common file format for mass spectrometry data.

Concepts.definition: An XML based common file format for mass spectrometry data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An open file format used to store neuroscience and neuroradiology imaging data obtained by MRI. The raw image data in NIfTI is saved as a 3d image.

Concepts.definition: An open file format used to store neuroscience and neuroradiology imaging data obtained by MRI. The raw image data in NIfTI is saved as a 3d image. It was developed by the Neuroimaging Informatics Technology Initiative (NIfTI).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file that contains MATLAB commands and function calls.

Concepts.definition: A file that contains MATLAB commands and function calls.

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Open Microscopy Environment Tagged Image File Format
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tagged image file format (TIFF) image file format that contains an Open Microscopy Environment (OME) XML metadata block in the file header for storing microscopy information (pixels and metadata) using the OME Data Model.

Concepts.longName: Open Microscopy Environment Tagged Image File Format
Concepts.definition: A tagged image file format (TIFF) image file format that contains an Open Microscopy Environment (OME) XML metadata block in the file header for storing microscopy information (pixels and metadata) using the OME Data Model.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An open file format created and controlled by Adobe Systems, for representing two-dimensional documents in a device independent and resolution independent fixed-layout document format. Each PDF file encapsulates a complete description of a 2D document that includes the text, fonts, images, and 2D vector graphics that compose the document. PDF files do not encode information that is specific to the application software, hardware, or operating system used to create or view the document. This feature ensures that a valid PDF will render exactly the same regardless of its origin or destination (but depending on font availability when fonts are not encapsulated in the file).

Concepts.definition: An open file format created and controlled by Adobe Systems, for representing two-dimensional documents in a device independent and resolution independent fixed-layout document format. Each PDF file encapsulates a complete description of a 2D document that includes the text, fonts, images, and 2D vector graphics that compose the document. PDF files do not encode information that is specific to the application software, hardware, or operating system used to create or view the document. This feature ensures that a valid PDF will render exactly the same regardless of its origin or destination (but depending on font availability when fonts are not encapsulated in the file).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A data format consisting of readable textual material maintained as a sequential file.

Concepts.definition: A data format consisting of readable textual material maintained as a sequential file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An extensible file format for lossless data compression of images.

Concepts.definition: An extensible file format for lossless data compression of images.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format used for writing scripts in the R programming language for execution within the R software environment, typically for statistical computation and graphics.

Concepts.definition: A file format used for writing scripts in the R programming language for execution within the R software environment, typically for statistical computation and graphics.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format for making dynamic documents written in R. It is written in plain text format and contains chunks of embedded R code.

Concepts.definition: A file format for making dynamic documents written in R. It is written in plain text format and contains chunks of embedded R code.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited file describing the relationships between samples, arrays, data and other objects used or produced during a microarray experiment.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited file describing the relationships between samples, arrays, data and other objects used or produced during a microarray experiment.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any file format designed to store molecular sequence data.

Concepts.definition: Any file format designed to store molecular sequence data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A specification for describing vector graphics using extensible markup language.

Concepts.definition: A specification for describing vector graphics using extensible markup language.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A plain text file that stores python code.

Concepts.definition: A plain text file that stores python code.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electronic file format based on TIFF that is used for storing multiple high-resolution images in a single electronic file.

Concepts.definition: An electronic file format based on TIFF that is used for storing multiple high-resolution images in a single electronic file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format generated by the Unix command-line utility tar (tape archive). It is used for collecting many files into one archive file.

Concepts.definition: A file format generated by the Unix command-line utility tar (tape archive). It is used for collecting many files into one archive file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A proprietary file format developed by Thermo Scientific to capture mass spectrometry data produced by Thermo mass spectrometers.

Concepts.definition: A proprietary file format developed by Thermo Scientific to capture mass spectrometry data produced by Thermo mass spectrometers.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file format where each line in the file contains a single piece of data and where each field or value in a line of data is separated from the next by a tab character.

Concepts.definition: A file format where each line in the file contains a single piece of data and where each field or value in a line of data is separated from the next by a tab character.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A data format consisting of readable textual material maintained as a sequential file.

Concepts.definition: A data format consisting of readable textual material maintained as a sequential file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A text-based electronic file used for storing gene sequence variation data. The first text section is composed of a header containing the metadata and keywords used in the file. This is followed by the body of the file which is tab-separated into eight mandatory data columns for each sample. Additionally, the body of the file can include an unlimited number of optional columns to record other sample-related data.

Concepts.definition: A text-based electronic file used for storing gene sequence variation data. The first text section is composed of a header containing the metadata and keywords used in the file. This is followed by the body of the file which is tab-separated into eight mandatory data columns for each sample. Additionally, the body of the file can include an unlimited number of optional columns to record other sample-related data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A proprietary binary file format used to store spreadsheet data in Microsoft Excel.

Concepts.definition: A proprietary binary file format used to store spreadsheet data in Microsoft Excel.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A proprietary file format developed by Microsoft that allows the user to save a spreadsheet created in Excel in an open XML-format. The file then can be read and opened by other spreadsheet-compatible applications.

Concepts.definition: A proprietary file format developed by Microsoft that allows the user to save a spreadsheet created in Excel in an open XML-format. The file then can be read and opened by other spreadsheet-compatible applications.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Extensible Markup Language

Concepts.definition: A general-purpose markup language for creating special-purpose markup languages. It is capable of describing many different kinds of data. Its primary purpose is to facilitate the sharing of data across different systems, particularly systems connected via the Internet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bitmap graphics file format utilizing tagged fields.

Concepts.definition: A bitmap graphics file format utilizing tagged fields.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A human-readable, tree-structured data-serialization language often used to create configuration files.

Concepts.definition: A human-readable, tree-structured data-serialization language often used to create configuration files. Data in YAML format can be serialized into text, or binary format.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An archive file format that supports lossless data compression. It is used to compress one or more files together into a single location.

Concepts.definition: An archive file format that supports lossless data compression. It is used to compress one or more files together into a single location.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A proprietary, encrypted XML-based, compressed electronic file format from Illumina Inc. for storing genome-wide profiling data. The data contains a summary of the intensity data generated from each probe used during a sequencing run.

Concepts.definition: A proprietary, encrypted XML-based, compressed electronic file format from Illumina Inc. for storing genome-wide profiling data. The data contains a summary of the intensity data generated from each probe used during a sequencing run.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A a tab-delimited containing information about an investigation, including its name, a description, the investigator's contact details, bibliographic references, and free text descriptions of any relevant protocols.

Concepts.definition: A a tab-delimited containing information about an investigation, including its name, a description, the investigator's contact details, bibliographic references, and free text descriptions of any relevant protocols.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A file compression format mostly used for color and greyscale photographs.

Concepts.definition: A file compression format mostly used for color and greyscale photographs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A discrete wavelet transform (DWT)-based compression standard electronic file format for storing video images.

Concepts.definition: A discrete wavelet transform (DWT)-based compression standard electronic file format for storing video images.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A common open standard file format and data interchange format that uses human-readable text consisting of attribute-value pairs and arrays to store and transmit data.

Concepts.definition: A common open standard file format and data interchange format that uses human-readable text consisting of attribute-value pairs and arrays to store and transmit data.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tab-delimited text file containing mutation information aggregated from variant call files (VCF) across a project, trial or study.

Concepts.definition: A tab-delimited text file containing mutation information aggregated from variant call files (VCF) across a project, trial or study.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of file that stores the results of intensity calculations of pixel values for DNA microarray image analysis. The data includes an intensity value, standard deviation of the intensity, the number of pixels used to calculate the intensity value, a flag to indicate an outlier as calculated by the algorithm, and a user defined flag indicating whether the feature should be excluded from future analysis. The file also stores the previously stated data for each feature on the probe array.

Concepts.definition: A type of file that stores the results of intensity calculations of pixel values for DNA microarray image analysis. The data includes an intensity value, standard deviation of the intensity, the number of pixels used to calculate the intensity value, a flag to indicate an outlier as calculated by the algorithm, and a user defined flag indicating whether the feature should be excluded from future analysis. The file also stores the previously stated data for each feature on the probe array.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An external index file created by the sequencing data archive alongside a compressed reference-oriented alignment map (CRAM) file. This index file is available in the same directory as the CRAM file and is required for selective access to the genomic sequence alignment data within the CRAM file.

Concepts.definition: An external index file created by the sequencing data archive alongside a compressed reference-oriented alignment map (CRAM) file. This index file is available in the same directory as the CRAM file and is required for selective access to the genomic sequence alignment data within the CRAM file.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A minimal base ASCII file format to facilitate the exchange of data matrices.

Concepts.definition: A minimal base ASCII file format to facilitate the exchange of data matrices.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An exchange format for peptides and proteins identified from mass spectra.

Concepts.definition: An exchange format for peptides and proteins identified from mass spectra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A format for the storage of numerical or pattern matrices in a dense (array format) or sparse (coordinate format) representation.

Concepts.definition: A format for the storage of numerical or pattern matrices in a dense (array format) or sparse (coordinate format) representation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A text file format used to store genomic paired-end sequencing data that includes coordinates and associated metadata.

Concepts.definition: A text file format used to store genomic paired-end sequencing data that includes coordinates and associated metadata.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An indexed binary format designed to permit fast random access to contact matrix heatmaps.

Concepts.definition: An indexed binary format designed to permit fast random access to contact matrix heatmaps.

ConceptualDomain.preferredDefinition: An organizational header for concepts representing mostly abstract entities.

Something distinguishable as an identifiable class based on common qualities.
